Class Timeout

java.lang.Object
  js.Disposable
      jsx.Task
          jsx.Timeout
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Runnable
public class Timeout
extends Task

Represents tasks that may be set to run after a specified amount of time.

A task of this class, as a runnable task, can be run by either its function version returned from its Task.getFunction() method or a call to its Interval.run() method. Besides, it can also get its function run after a specified amount of time like what Js.setTimeout(JsFunction, Number) does, by a simple call to its set(Number) method, or cancel the pending execution by a call to its clear() method like what Js.clearTimeout(Object) does.

A subclass of this class must make sure that its function version, method run() and pending function are all executing the same code.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:
Js.setTimeout(JsFunction), Js.setTimeout(JsFunction, Number), Js.clearTimeout(Object), Interval

Constructor Detail

Timeout

protected Timeout()

The default constructor.

A subclass must override run() to make the task runnable when its constructor invokes this one, because this constructor sets the Task.funct field to a function that invokes the run() method.

Since:
1.0

run()

Timeout

public Timeout(java.lang.Runnable r)

Constructs from an existing runnable object.

This constructor sets the Task.funct field of this task to the function of the argument task. Note that, the run() method has been designed to simply invoke the Task.funct function. Override it with caution in a subclass where this constructor is invoked.

Since:
1.0
